  accentWord="Electrical"
  subhead="It is 10:30am on a Tuesday. You are terminating a new Schneider Acti 9 iC60 consumer unit in a detached house in Wantage — sixteen circuits, each conductor stripped to the correct length, sleeved where required, and torqued into the RCBO terminals with a calibrated torque screwdriver. The busbar clicks are verified, the neutral bar connections checked, and the incoming supply tails are the last to be connected. Three calls come in between 10am and noon. Your phone is on the kitchen worktop, the consumer unit is in the hallway cupboard, and your hands hold stripped conductors. Without Missed Call Text Back, one voicemail — 'need an electrician' — two hang-ups. With it, all three receive texts within seconds. The first replies at 10:45am: 'Hi — property developer, converting a Victorian pub in Wallingford into six flats plus a ground-floor restaurant. Need full electrical design and install: three-phase incoming supply, main switchroom, submains to seven distribution boards, individual flat consumer units with RCBOs and pre-payment meter tails, restaurant commercial kitchen electrics (three-phase oven, combi, extraction), fire alarm BS 5839 Cat L1, emergency lighting BS 5266, structured Cat6a data and CCTV containment. Design-and-build preferred. Conversion starts in ten weeks. Call when you can — this is a priority.' At the lunch break you review. Wednesday you call: Wallingford Victorian pub to 6 flats + restaurant, three-phase, main switchroom, 7 DBs, RCBO flat boards, pre-payment tails, commercial kitchen three-phase, BS 5839 L1, BS 5266, Cat6a, CCTV, D&B, 10-week start."
  scenario="It is 4pm on a rainy November Wednesday. You have been in the ceiling void of a three-storey office in the city centre since 8am — running 175 metres of Cat6a structured data cabling through cable basket containment, each blue cable dressed neatly in the basket and labelled at both ends. Six missed calls between 8am and 4pm. Without Missed Call Text Back, you emerge at 4pm: six unknowns, one voicemail — 'EICR needed urgently' — five gone permanently. With Missed Call Text Back, all six received texts. Reply one: 'homeowner Headington — EICR failed with C1 and C2s, solicitor demanding remediation for house sale, exchange in 5 weeks.' Reply two: 'main contractor Didcot — 20 houses need first-fix starting January, can you tender?' Reply three: 'letting agent — rewire needed on a 1940s HMO, 6 bedrooms, old rubber cable.' Reply four: 'homeowner Botley — want EV charger installed, 7kW Easee One, driveway, need dedicated circuit.' Reply five: 'architect — lighting design for a barn conversion near Bampton, LED throughout, DALI dimming, external landscape lighting.' Reply six: 'facilities manager — fire alarm BS 5839 L2 upgrade, 4-storey office, conventional to addressable.' Six leads. Wednesday evening you triage — the C1 house sale first, the 20-house tender second."
